So, in my journey towards an education in social work, I've got a clear path in mind. I aim to serve the Division of Family and Children Services, focusing on assisting children who've been abused or neglected, and providing support to troubled families. The values I bring to this field are service, respect, a strong ethical nature, a commitment to enhancing relationships between others, and a dedication to growing professionally to stay competent. These values aren't just essential for social workers; they're integral to who I am personally.

I've always desired to help others, but the career path wasn't clear. Through high school and college, I witnessed individuals avoid problems in denial and use less-than-ideal coping mechanisms. Seeing this, I chose a Bachelor’s degree in Psychology. After graduating from Piedmont College in 2009, I took a break, unsure of my career path. One summer, a friend introduced me to a 16-year-old boy fleeing his abusive parents. The next day, he called the police. I drove to his house to check if I could help and talked to the parents about their son's situation. They seemed nervous and blamed their son's "manipulative" behavior. This experience made me consider a career in social work to support children in similar family disputes.

Another crucial value for social work is social justice. Society claims the individual is important, yet we often strive to be like "everyone else." This isn't unique individualism. Throughout school, I protested against social injustice: coloring my hair, dressing to express myself, piercing my ears beyond traditional norms, being open about my involvement with GSBA, and fighting against racism and discrimination. I believe in social justice and will continue to stand against injustice.

This paper explores the Biological and Sociocultural models in relation to the sleep disorder insomnia. The Biological model delves into inherited genetic information and medical aspects of health, while the Sociocultural model examines environmental relationships and their impacts on race, ethnicity, demographics, and socioeconomic status. The review of insomnia examines these models and discusses each piece of research to better explain them. The strengths and weaknesses of the research findings are also critiqued.

A sleep disorder can be categorized as a Primary sleep disorder, a sleep disorder related to another mental disorder, or a sleep disorder related to other issues. Primary sleep disorders are Dyssomnias or Parasomnias, while those related to another mental disorder are linked to Axis I or Axis II disorders. Other categories include sleep disorders caused by medical complications or substance intake. Dyssomnias like Primary Insomnia, Primary Hypersomnia, Narcolepsy, Breathing-Related Sleep Disorder, Circadian Rhythm Sleep Disorder, and Dyssomnia Not Otherwise Specified (NOS), and Parasomnias such as Nightmare Disorder, Sleep Terror Disorder, Sleepwalking Disorder, and Parasomnias Not Otherwise Specified, define these disorders. The review focuses primarily on insomnia and the broader topic of primary sleep disorders in relation to the Biological and Sociocultural models.

This essay explores Central Auditory Processing Disorder, or CAPD, from three angles: its definition, diagnosis, and how educators can assist students with CAPD in mainstream classrooms.

CAPD is a condition where the central nervous system struggles to process auditory information effectively. This doesn't mean individuals with CAPD are hearing impaired; rather, their brains have difficulty translating sounds into meaningful information. People with CAPD can hear normally but may struggle to distinguish words from background noise.

CAPD has been studied since the mid-1950s, initially referred to as "auditory imperception." Italian researchers Bocca, Calearo, and Cassinari began testing children with communicative disorders in 1954, and Kimura introduced dichotic testing in 1961. A 1977 conference further spurred research on CAPD.

CAPD can manifest in various ways, such as difficulty in locating sounds, distinguishing between acoustic events, recognizing sound patterns, or differentiating changes in speech. Individuals with CAPD may also struggle to synthesize sound cues and determine the sequence of auditory information.

Diagnosing CAPD involves observing the patient's listening behavior or performance on auditory function tests, which can be conducted by audiologists, speech-language pathologists, psychologists, and others. No single test exists for a conclusive diagnosis, and the cause of CAPD remains unknown. Common tests include presenting multiple simultaneous auditory stimuli and asking the patient to identify certain items. Advanced tests may involve recording acoustic signals within the ear and measuring responses.

Teachers in mainstream classrooms can play a significant role in assisting students with CAPD. They can help by creating a calm, quiet environment, clearly stating instructions, and ensuring the student receives preferential seating. Visual aids and repetition can also be beneficial, as can breaking tasks into smaller, manageable parts.

Another month has come and gone, and not much has changed in my life. But there's one thing I want to talk about. I finally finished the beta version of the tradenet website, after a lot of dragging my feet. It's been a process of adding and improving, and I think I'm going to register a domain and get it online by the middle of January. The delay was due to a lack of funds and a way to transfer it to the web hosting company. My partner will get his credit card in January, so that's when we'll set it up. And of course, I also flunked accounting. I knew I was close to failing, but I didn't think I'd actually flunk. I put in an appeal to the course coordinator, but I don't have high hopes. On the bright side, I got distinctions for law and economics. I guess if you enjoy a course, you're more motivated to do well in it. But then, you enjoy a course when it's easy to understand. Hmm, a catch 22 situation. Anyway, I'll get the appeal result this week. I'm hoping for the best. Otherwise, nothing much happened.

Now, about the other big thing that's been going on. I have this affliction called shyness. When I talk to strangers, especially those of the opposite sex, I turn into jelly. I can't think, I start to tremble, and I just freeze up. It happened today at the YEN meeting. I had to tell Genevieve I hadn't gotten the club mailing list invitation yet. I thought it would be easy, but it wasn't. I care too much about what others think of me, and my brain shuts down. She tried to be nice, but I didn't react well to it. I hope I didn't look like a dweeb. But I'm working on it. One of the main reasons I joined YEN is to force myself into situations where I have to interact with strangers, especially those from the opposite gender. If I want to get anywhere in life, I can't do it on my own. It's not so bad with people I know well, but there's still a fear inside me. That's why I've never had the nerve to get into any relationship. It's frustrating to want something so badly but be too afraid to reach out and get it. No matter what happens, I will overcome this 'disability,' if you will. And the only way to do that is through increased interaction. The other problem I have is positive thinking, which affects my motivation. It's all my parents' fault. Especially my mom. She's so negative all the time. It might seem unfilial to say this, but it's true. She comes from a society and upbringing that isn't generally known for achievements. Now she's passed it on to me. But the positive thing is, now that I'm aware of this shortcoming, I can work towards eliminating it. I Have to be smart about it.

I talked to the YEN guy I met through Darren. I can't remember his name. He's a total 'Adam Knoo' convert. It might be unwise to turn evangelical for anything, but in this case, it's positive. He made me realize how negative my thoughts have been lately. How small I've been thinking. So negative I'm disgusted with myself. I will stop using the word 'try' and use the word 'MUST.' It's amazing how much difference a word and thought makes in your life. So I MUST come up with a study and work schedule on Sunday and I MUST follow through with that schedule. There! That's settled then. A paradigm shift in actions and thought.

Well, Kings has gotten himself a girlfriend. Wouldn't have thought that would happen anytime soon. But life can sometimes blindside you when you least expect it. So there it is. My kemosabe in bachelorhood arms has deserted me. Can't say I blame him though. Except the reason for him to get together with this girl is rather suspect. I'll never be sure whether he got together with her just to prove to himself that he could get a girlfriend or that he's really sincerely into this girl. Only way to find out is to just ask him directly, but that would just make our friendship take a weird turn. Oh well.

So, onto something else. Been a long while since I added any new entries. But hot damn! Lazy bones strikes again. Sometimes I wonder why I bothered to have a blog in the first place. Well, it's the school holidays now. Finished the exams. I hope to pass all four papers. Anyway, the accounts paper was a bust. Same feeling as the stats paper last semester. Probably gonna flunk accounts. But there's always a chance I'll pass, right? Well, tomorrow, or I should say today, I'm gonna go down to the registry of companies and I'm gonna register a business partnership with Kumar. It's been a long time coming. Gonna call the new company 'Epac Trading Company' in honour of the earlier supposed but on hold partnership with the other two future partners for Entrepac. Well, we'll see what happens tomorrow then. Oh and I'm working on tradenet now. Damn I loathe programming. But I gave my word that I'll do it and I don't like to break it. Though sometimes there are extenuating circumstances. Heck, there's always an excuse not to do something, right?

I just read this article, specifically the section referring to the remarks made by Bill Cosby. In it he talks about the culture of victimism in America. This got me to think about the culture of victimism in the civilised world as we know it today. I get tired when I hear people blaming everything but themselves for their less than desired life situations. Or saying it's meant to be. In my humble opinion, unless you are mentally incapacitated, you, and only you, are responsible for the life you lead. There is no two ways about it. What's the point of blaming everything for your troubles? Why not get off your ass and do something about it? I'd like to think that I am doing so through actively taking actions that have a specific life goal in mind. You can't go anywhere if you don't have anywhere you want to go to. So I suppose the key is that you should decide upon a goal that you want to strive towards. But it's not just goal setting that's important. It must be with a sense of discipline that you work towards your goal with. Though that by no means guarantees success, success cannot be achieved otherwise.

Slept at 10 last night. That's something I haven't done in such a long time. I actually can't remember the last time I went to bed before midnight. There's just so many better things to do than sleep. Guess it finally caught up with me. Woke up at half past 11 the next morning. A good 13 1/2 hours of sleep. Funnily enough, it wasn't as refreshing as I would have thought it would have been. I could actually stay awake throughout the lecture today. Can't say the same thing about paying attention though. That's what getting enough Zs can do for you. I must study econ tomorrow. Yes. Must. That's the power of suggestion. Saying and thinking are two totally different things when you turn them into action. Saying that you MUST instead of saying that you will TRY. Now I know. So I MUST complete the first three topics tomorrow. Not that I've got any better things to do. Yes, I know it's ambitious considering my procrastinative past. But I MUST do it. After all, I am answering it MYSELF. And lying to yourself is far worse than lying to anyone else, wouldn't you agree?

Well, it's a week and a half till the next semester begins. Man, the holidays flew past in a blink of an eye, didn't they? This is probably the last holiday that I will have to just laze around and do pretty much nothing. The next holiday, at the end of this year, I'll probably be busy with the DPP project (one big mother of a research project) and with the starting up of the tuition centre. The following holiday, during mid 2005, I'll be in Melbourne at RMIT, for most of that month. So that doesn't leave much time for breathers in between. Phew! From here on out, it'll be one mad rush. And that's just the beginning of life then. I look toward it with mixed feelings really. On one hand, it'll be great to be able to start earning my keep. But on the other hand, I don't want to leave the security of school so soon. But time marches on. And there is nothing anyone can do about it. All I can do is to face it head on and hope that life doesn't chew me up and spit me out. But that's just being pessimistic. Remember the glass is half full!

Well, I was just in one of my rhetoric moods just now. I was thinking of how sad it was that good friends can grow apart as you grow up. You gain new perspectives as you grow and those might now be the same as your friends. Like you're in different realities. Sometimes you grow apart because of differing views and sometimes it's because of circumstances. Some of which are not under your control but most of which are. Things like gaining new ideological beliefs, new social groups or just something as simple as getting a new job. Any of which can cause you to not make contact as often as you would like. I used to believe that it was their fault for not keeping in touch. But then I realized that I was as much at fault as anyone else in my life. People walk in and walk out of your life. You can try to keep them from walking out but ultimately, it's their choice. Guess that's why you have to choose your friends carefully. But then again, if you are too guarded in your choices, you might be artificially restricting yourself. Ah the choices we all make. I've had many good people in my life. It's sad to reminisce on the good times past as you know the chances of regaining those times are slim to none. So there's no use dwelling on them. But you don't want to discount their value in helping to shape you into the person that you are today. And yet, you don't want to let them hold you back from becoming the person that you're going to be tomorrow. Sigh.

This doesn't happen much when you're a teenager but it starts when you reach adulthood. You wish to be as carefree as you were then. Letting your parents worry for you. Reality was just for other people. You lived in a cocoon, in your own world. Ah the good old days.

Well, another tale of German colonial rule to ponder upon. We all know how infamous it was for its cruelty, with the Ovaherero and Nama genocide in South West Africa being a stark testament. But let's not oversimplify things. The German colonial empire was as varied as the lands it conquered, with diverse policies and ruling styles. Educational provision followed suit, with significant differences across colonies. Now, when the British took over German East Africa (Tanganyika) in 1919, they found a well-educated African population to their surprise. Similarly, German efforts in Kamerun and other colonies were met with praise by contemporary authors.

But you know what was quite different? South West Africa, now Namibia. Unlike East Africa, where the government played a crucial role in schooling natives, the natives' education was mostly left to missionary societies with limited government support. The Europeans, however, got the royal treatment - state schools were established, and missionary schools were heavily supported and regulated. These policies had long-lasting effects on Namibia, even after the Germans were gone. Other German colonies had literate Africans, but in Namibia, the majority remained uneducated and illiterate.

Why the stark contrast? Social, political, and economic factors played a huge part. This paper wants to delve into these factors, focusing on new research on how settlers and colonial authorities viewed the native Africans.

Research on colonial education is vast, with many sources in German from the early twentieth century. These works aimed to describe educational systems. Later English studies compared and analyzed these systems, highlighting significant differences. Cohen's work on education in South West Africa and East Africa is particularly notable, comparing the two colonies and discussing the factors behind their differences. The large settler population in South West Africa, Cohen argues, explains many differences in its educational system.

Now, let's talk climate. South West Africa had a moderately pleasant climate, with many desert areas. This hospitable environment attracted a significant European population. By 1913, nearly 15,000 whites lived there, while East Africa, the next largest settler colony, had only 5,336.

So, let's talk about the evolution of popular music over the past century. Popular music has grown into a sprawling landscape with so many genres that it's tough to list them all. But let's zero in on one of the most diverse and expressive genres: Heavy Metal. This genre has been around for about 40 years and has spawned a plethora of sub and sub-sub genres, each with its unique sound. Heavy Metal is known for its wide range of emotions, mainly leaning towards the darker side of the spectrum. It's diverse and flexible, allowing musicians to create their own niches and sub-genres.

Today, the Heavy Metal scene is chock-full of different groups, making it hard to pin down exactly what Heavy Metal is. It's difficult to understand the current metal music landscape without first grasping what the Heavy Metal movement is and why it's more than just a genre.

A few decades before the Surrealists started painting their dreamlike masterpieces, Henri Rousseau was already crafting his own dreams, both literally and figuratively. The Dream, a 1910 painting by the renowned Post-Impressionist artist, captures not only a woman in awe of her dreamland but also Rousseau’s own personal aspirations as an artist. Since he started his journey, he yearned for recognition, acceptance, and praise from fellow artists and art enthusiasts, yet faced a tough internal dilemma: whether to conform to or mimic certain painting styles to gain acceptance or to remain creatively independent and unique. The Dream is Rousseau’s magnum opus that best reflects his career-long struggle to choose between these two paths.

To understand The Dream through this lens, one must first delve into Rousseau’s biography. Henri Rousseau was born on May 21, 1844, in Laval, northwest France. His father was a tinsmith and hardware dealer who enjoyed bourgeois prosperity. Unlike his peers, Rousseau didn’t receive formal art training; instead, he worked as a gabelou—a municipal toll service employee—until the age of forty. He was known as douanier, a customs inspector. The death of his first wife, Clémence, followed by the loss of eight infant children left Rousseau with only one daughter, Julia, and deep grief. Painting became his refuge and fresh start.

Rousseau’s desire for art world acceptance is understandable given his context. He was uneducated in formal painting and began late in life, working alongside other talented but more famous artists. He longed for recognition like Matisse, but their motivations differed. Matisse feared painting tritely, while Rousseau sought a conventional style to be admitted to the Artiste Français.

Many a great thinker has pondered the deep connection between ethics and aesthetics, between truth and beauty. I believe there's a fundamental reason for this. As John Keats asserts in "Ode on a Grecian Urn", "Beauty is truth, truth beauty—That is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know." Much of what we learn in life comes from education or experience. Yet, we often appreciate ethics and aesthetics without being formally taught in these ways. Both ethics and aesthetics are attempts to describe rather than prescribe. Our studies of morality and beauty are usually efforts to explain why something is beautiful or moral, rather than rules for creating or judging good art or moral behavior.

Critiquing art or morals often falls short of capturing their essence. For instance, a discussion about the worth of da Vinci's Mona Lisa might revolve around concepts like foreground, background, contrast, or cultural context, but these don't explain why it's considered good art. Often, when asked about a favorite work of art or literature, people say, "There's just something about it," followed by a more complex explanation. Both art and morals can't be fully reduced to their qualities. As Flannery O'Connor notes, "A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way . . . you tell a story because a statement would be inadequate." Similarly, ethics shares this transcendental nature. As Wittgenstein suggests, "It is clear that ethics cannot be expressed. / Ethics is transcendental. /" It's this "je ne sais quoi," this ineffable quality, that makes both art and morality so powerful and links them together.

I believe morality and art are closely related because we experience them most deeply at a noumenal level, to use a Kantian term. They affect us at a level we can experience but not fully explain. This connection is strongest in literature. As McKean states, "What most distinguishes literature from the other arts, what is, in truth, unique about the art, is its moral quality. It may be that moral standards are inappropriate to other arts, music, for instance, but they seem to be as relevant to literature as they are to life itself. Living necessarily involves values . . . Literature is important to us precisely because of the values we find there."

Today's Germany stands tall as a united nation, with a unique cultural fusion that stretches from the foothills of the Alps in Munich to the Baltic Sea city of Kiel. This rich cultural tapestry is felt from Cologne by the Rhine, through the heart of Germany, to the Elbe's banks in the Saxon city of Dresden. Given this unique heritage, it's not surprising that modern Germany is a blend of diverse origins and tribes.

Germania, the ancestral home of the Germans, has a name shrouded in debate among scholars and historians. While Tacitus believed the name stemmed from a Germanic tribe called the Tungrians, and others argue it derived from a Gallic word or an Old Irish word, 'garim' meaning 'to shout', the exact origin remains uncertain. For instance, Tacitus wrote in his AD 98 work, "De Origine et situ Germanorum", that he considered the Germans to be indigenous and not mixed with other races. He further noted that no one would willingly leave the warmth of Rome for the harsh climate and tough ways of Germania unless it was their home. Indeed, as the Germanic tribes started appearing in the mid-first century, they lived on the empire's borders, trading goods and skills with the Romans. The Romans would occasionally send expeditions to these lands, but they usually returned to their vast empire, leaving the Germanic tribes to live on the frontier.

Downwards, I stared, my mind blankly comprehending the view before me. Silent, unemotionally, my practiced awareness studied but refused to relate the object of study to any abstract understanding. Thoughts slipped in and out almost faster than they appeared, my consciousness working so smoothly and cleanly that it felt like I had no real thoughts of my own, just an active and liquid experience of what I was looking at. Once, following advice from an artist I worked with, I bought an art instruction book called The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain. I'd wanted to learn how to draw since I was six, and this book teaches everything from understanding a pencil to processes the brain uses to interpret lines. One technique it teaches is to place a square frame around any picture the artist wishes to study, transforming an overwhelmingly detailed picture into an easily grasped one. Staring down at the bowl in front of me, I couldn't mentally project that artist’s frame. I was so overwhelmed, so awed that I could only stand and gaze in wonderment. Picasso went through his blue phase, Monet loved greenery, Italian Renaissance masters displayed a rainbow of colors. If I had any pretensions of casting my perspective as worthy of the title Artistic then before me were the beginnings of my picture, the start of my story, Work in Brown. Fingertips alighted on my chosen implement of artistry, muscles tightening and relaxing as my hand passed through space, my mind’s will given shape and form in what could have been the most creative moment of my life. Water swirled, serene and smooth, crystal clear and clean. Flakes of matter broke away from the whole and were carried away to nothingness. Muscles tightened, jerking and spasming a little more quickly and anxiously the second time, my hand smacked the handle of the toilet again. The offensive brown package refused to move, stuck like a slug on the bottom of the toilet. Mop gripped loosely in hand, feet set a foot apart, green tie knotted uncomfortably around my throat, I frowned slightly as I stared at the rude bundle of processed animal and plant matter someone had left as a message for the suckers who cleaned the bathrooms at Rite Aid. A few more flushes, a few more tranquil introspective moments to myself, then my hand moved towards the wall to my right, gripped the sheet at the end of the toilet paper, and began mummifying itself until it resembled an oven mitt. Standing up straight, then bending at the waist, my hand dipped slowly into the bowl, like a mother going into an oven for the Thanksgiving turkey.

So, another year is coming to a close, and let me tell you, it's been more than a little bit of a shock. Teenagers are dying behind the wheel, and it's a grim reality that's been building for some time. The National Institutes of Health has been saying it all along: the teen brain just isn't ready for the dangers of driving, and that inexperience is at the root of it all. Not only does this lead to more accidents, but it also increases the risk of rollovers, speeding, and driving off the road. And when you add in the fact that teens often drive with their peers—because, let's face it, that's how they roll—well, it's a perfect storm of disaster.

Several states have tried to put a stop to this with temporary provisional licenses that limit driving hours and prohibit other teens as passengers. But let me tell you, these are just Band-Aid solutions. The issue is that, as a group, the youngest drivers just aren't equipped to handle the risks and responsibilities. Even seasoned psychologists like Marvin Zuckerman think that 18 is too young to issue a regular driver's license. USA Today reports that he's done research showing that teens under 19-20 are still on a high-risk thrill-seeking streak. It makes sense then to delay driving until that tendency starts to level out. If we keep giving licenses to young teens now, we're setting ourselves up for a whole lot of tragedy in the upcoming years. By 2010, the Baby Boomer's babies will be ready to hit the road, and millions of new teen drivers will be on the streets.

What we need is straightforward legislation. Schools could keep teaching driver's education, but no one under 18 could be driving a car. A provisional permit could still be issued, and a set number of practical training hours would be required. California, for instance, currently requires 6 hours of behind-the-wheel training and 50 hours of practice with an adult. Since this is a problem that affects teens across the country, uniform, national legislation would be a sensible and effective way to protect teens everywhere.

Now, this idea isn't exactly new, but it's time for action. We can't keep looking the other way while our teens are dying behind the wheel. It's time for a change.

So I decided to take a look at the Library of Congress’s collection of early Edison films. I wanted to check out all of the trick films, which numbered fifteen from 1895 to 1901. These films are known for their creative editing techniques used to create illusions. My study mainly involved describing the poetics of most trick films and looking at the unique traits in a few of the later ones. Most of these films were set-bound, using a frontal proscenium, and had no camera movement. Typically, long and medium shots were employed, and each trick film was composed of one shot. However, some films from the early 1900s dared to break these rules by including multiple shots.

One common feature among these trick films is their filming within an interior set, framed within a frontal proscenium. The camera doesn't move from its proscenium position to follow characters or objects. This style was heavily influenced by theatre and vaudeville and magic acts. One example is Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel (1900), where actors enter from the right and move back and forth horizontally. Even when they exit the frame, the camera doesn't follow them. This composition led to shots being long and medium in nature, borrowing from theatre traditions where the audience views the entire performance within the stage's borders. Actors seldom moved towards the camera, so close-ups weren't used.

Trick films typically follow the rule of one conceptual shot equaling a single film, limiting their length to about a minute or less. This also restricted their dramatic or narrative usage, with most focusing on short vaudeville-style tricks like magic and disappearing acts with little story. However, in trick films, a conceptual shot might consist of several physical shots joined together to create illusions of apparition or disappearing, like in The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots (1895). A careful watch reveals the moment when the physical shot with Mary’s severed “head” starts, though the film is conceptually one shot to the viewer.

John Taylor from Caroline was an early and passionate advocate for Republicanism. Despite being primarily an agriculturalist and having a short career in politics, he was renowned for his commitment and outspoken nature in matters of personal liberty and governance. His dedication to agriculture and his political experiences shaped his strong opinions on sovereignty, the Constitution, and even the judicial system.

Taylor saw the United States as having a unique chance to establish an ideal system, as there were no native traditions to hinder its creators. He believed in the innate rights of man and their interdependence, arguing that if one right was denied, all would fail, and the remaining rights would be less valuable. These rights, he thought, should be outside the government's reach. He believed that a "state of nature" allowed the powerful and cunning to thrive, but in a society, this should not be the case.

To create this ideal society, Taylor believed a government must acknowledge the inherent good and evil within humanity. He was rigid in his belief that morality was dualistic, asserting, "As government is exercised by man, all its virtues and vices must be human." He defined good principles as those that protected private property, promoted agriculture, and discouraged capitalism. A government founded on these principles would function fairly, regardless of its leaders, who would inevitably be driven by avarice and self-interest. Self-interest, Taylor believed, was a powerful force but only became evil when it led to sub-societies exploiting others. A good government, he argued, was needed to control man's natural evil and should be closely monitored to prevent the adoption of harmful principles.

Like many Republicans of his time, Taylor advocated for a strict interpretation of the Constitution. He favored a limited Federal government, with no more rights or powers than explicitly stated. He recognized that an extensive Federal government could be expensive and potentially oppressive. However, he believed that a strict, literal interpretation could become corrupt without considering the intent of the founders. Furthermore, he viewed the Declaration of Independence as the true charter of the United States, as it more clearly described the country as a union of sovereign states rather than a single nation.

Well, another month has gone by, and I have a whole bunch of stuff to talk about that happened. First off, take a look at Figure 17, and you'll see a noticeable drop in commuter log submissions in the third month of our project. That's a bit of a bummer because I'm not sure why that happened. I mean, it’s New England, so the weather could be a factor with people not commuting by bike or on foot due to the cold. Also, it's the end of the fall semester, so everyone's heads are down doing schoolwork or processing grades. And December brings the holiday season, so some folks might have just forgotten about filling out the commuter log. Plus, classes don't resume until late January, and that could also account for the low numbers in February. But none of that explains the February dip. It's possible that projects like this start with a lot of energy and excitement, which naturally wears off over time. To counteract this, we launched the Carpool Challenge Week in March to give the project a boost, and it did help increase log submissions. So, we faced the challenge of keeping the momentum going, especially with the holiday and semester breaks that are common in higher education. Another hurdle is that people just really enjoy driving their cars, which is deeply ingrained in our culture. To get folks interested in alternative commuting, we handed out a ton of gift certificates to all sorts of places like local restaurants, coffee shops, and bookstores. We even considered giving away bicycles or hybrid cars, which could have helped combat that dip in engagement. The prizes we offered were pretty solid at first, but if we had announced bigger prizes like bikes or hybrid cars throughout the project, it might have kept participation higher. For instance, announcing a bike giveaway in December and a hybrid or electric car giveaway in January could have increased engagement instead of it decreasing.

So here's a quick rundown on ETFs. An ETF, or exchange traded fund, is a security that mirrors an index, a commodity, or a basket of assets like an index fund, but it's more flexible and trades like a stock on an exchange. You get the diversification of an index fund and the perks of single stock ownership, such as the ability to sell short, buy on margin, or purchase as few as one share in any transaction. These benefits are quite appealing, but ETFs typically have lower expense ratios than average mutual funds. The downside is you have to pay a commission for any trades involving ETFs, just like with stock orders. Another upside is the wide variety of funds available. But hey, it's always good to check if these stated benefits, like diversification, actually materialize and to what extent. For now, let's look at the ETF IHF and compare it against its top 10 holdings, which make up 63.58% of all assets in the ETF. Below are these top 10 holdings and their respective percentages.

To gauge how well these ten stocks represent the ETF IHF as a whole, we can normalize the current % of assets to 100% and calculate the contributions of each stock to a portfolio’s Beta and Return if the portfolio was made up entirely of these 10 stocks, in the proportion they have in the ETF. Here are the calculations:

From this chart, it's clear that a portfolio consisting of only the top 10 holdings has a 6.11% higher return than the ETF, which is a 16% increase. Additionally, the Beta of the top ten holdings is 0.12 lower than the ETF as a whole. So, it looks like a portfolio of just the top 10 holdings could yield higher returns with a lower Beta. However, these two portfolios might not be statistically different from each other.

To determine if these portfolios are indeed statistically different, we need to calculate the standard deviation of each of the top 10 stocks and normalize it to 100% to compare their accumulated standard deviation with that of the ETF IHF.

One of Edgar Allan Poe's standout poems is "Dream-Land." In this work, he employs the term "Thulé" in lines 6 and 56, a reference traced back by Mabbott to Virgil. Virgil utilized the term for an island north of Britain, considered the edge of the known world. While Virgil did indeed use the term, there's a more contemporary source to which some credit should be given. Poe was particularly captivated by German authors.

This is notable as it reveals Poe's familiarity with Goethe's writings. Karl J. Arndt, in his book "Poe’s Politian and Goethe’s Mignon," discusses the similarities between their poems, concluding that Poe was likely imitating Goethe.

The Oxford Companion to English Literature notes that Goethe was famous for his poetic drama "Faust," published in two parts—the first in 1808 and the second in 1832, the year of Goethe's death. Within Faust's second part lies a short poem titled "The King of Thulé." In this piece, a king loses his wife after she gives him a goblet. Upon his wife's passing, he becomes a heavy drinker and mourns, eventually deciding it is time for him to die. He bestows his possessions on his children, except for the goblet, which he throws into the ocean before dying. The King of Thule and the description in "Dream-Land" share striking similarities, possibly serving as a dark reflection of Poe's own struggles and reliance on drinking as a coping mechanism. Faust was also adapted into a romantic drama by H.P. Grattan in 1842, only a year before Poe’s use of the term "Thule" in "The Pit and the Pendulum."

Poe mentions "ultma Thule" once in his collected works, but he uses the term "Thule" twice in "Dream-Land," bookending the poem. "The King of Thule" and "Dream-Land" can be considered companion pieces. In "Dream-Land," the speaker describes the landscape of Thule, a dark and lonely place haunted by dead friends, and sees a world shaded without color. These scenes echo "The King of Thule" by Goethe, as the king is in mourning, lonely, and has lost the will to rule or live. The entire poem reads as if the speaker has stepped into Goethe's poem.

Goethe was a significant writer whose work Poe would have known, not only through his admiration for Tennyson but also through the many reproductions of his works after their original publication.

Under California law, could a customer who slipped and fell on an applesauce spill in a grocery store be awarded punitive damages by proving the store manager acted with malice? Specifically, the manager was informed twice about the spill but failed to clean it for half an hour because he was having dinner. A judge is unlikely to dismiss Jennifer Palmer's punitive damage claim outright. To succeed, she must show that the manager's actions were willful and conscious disregard for the likely harm, and that the actions were despicable. Palmer could argue that the manager should have known about the probable harm since multiple customers were injured from slipping before her accident. She might also claim that the manager's failure to address the spill was despicable, considering there were already six slip-and-fall incidents in 2009. On October 13, 2009, at 5:00 pm, an employee informed the manager about the applesauce spill. The manager responded that he was on dinner break and didn't have time to deal with it. Another employee notified the manager about the spill at 5:15 pm, and the manager gave the same response. At 5:30 pm, Jennifer Palmer slipped and fell on the spill, sustaining a serious back injury. Before Palmer's accident, five slip-and-fall incidents had been reported at D&D Markets in 2009. Palmer is now suing D&D for compensatory and punitive damages, and we are considering filing a motion for partial summary against the punitive damage claim. In California, a plaintiff can recover punitive damages for a breach of an obligation not arising out of a contract if the defendant acted with "oppression, fraud, or malice." The statute defines malice as conduct intended to cause harm, or absent intent, the conduct must be "despicable" and committed with "a willful and conscious disregard of the rights or safety of others." Courts have considered conduct malicious when the defendant was aware of the probable dangerous consequences of their conduct and deliberately failed to avoid them.

So, four years ago, I enrolled in a CBC course on Islam. The main topic of debate in the class was whether Islam is inherently hostile. I find this question more pertinent now than ever, given the shift in mass media's perception of Islam post-9/11. In 2001, I couldn’t have imagined a presidential candidate like Barack Obama, with a Muslim background, becoming a reality in America. It’s fascinating how the media’s view has swung from hostility to extreme tolerance.

The Prophet Muhammad's biography piqued my interest. According to historical accounts, Muhammad’s rise to power and the spread of Islam contradict the image of him portrayed in the biography. I've always heard that Muhammad forced conversions, conquering tribes and imposing Islam upon them. However, the biography presents him as a humble martyr, misunderstood and even humbled. People slowly came to recognize the 'truth' in his teachings and sought him out.

There are striking parallels between Muhammad's 'miracles' and Jesus' ministry. For instance, Muhammad multiplied a small amount of mutton and milk to feed forty men, a feat reminiscent of Jesus' own miracle. This style of writing makes Muhammad seem like a humble prophet who didn't need to prove anything, but simply lived in truth and miracles. This downplays the miracle and life of Jesus, making it seem like Muhammad is being used to take credit for Jesus' life and personhood.

Moreover, the biography often presents stories of self-proclaimed converts to Islam, illustrating that they 'found the truth' on their own. However, many of these accounts are third-hand, with the author relaying stories heard from others. I find this method unconvincing because it makes the stories seem less credible and more suspicious.

What bothers me most is how the biography elevates Muhammad, depicting him as a godly, humble, wise, and gentle man. However, historical records show Muhammad was not as gentle and humble as presented. I wonder if Muslims today are aware of the true history behind Muhammad’s rise to power.

The teachings of Jesus, as he held them during his lifetime, were swiftly set aside in the evolution of Christian thought following his life. If we observe this historical trajectory in broad terms, we notice a pattern of Christianity straying increasingly from its origins. Today, the world exhibits a growing awareness and unprecedented progressive tendency. While traditionalists persist and resist any thinking beyond what they've been taught, this segment of the population might not have a substantial impact on the whole. Among Christians, historical awareness will significantly increase in future years. There will be a rising desire to differentiate the doctrines that have been added to Christianity over time from Jesus' original intentions. This process may take decades or even centuries, but the outcome is inevitable: a reversal in the trend of Christian history. A movement will grow in numbers, peeling away layers of doctrine, as if the clock were turning backward, until only the core of Jesus' teachings remain. When this trend sweeps through the United States and Europe, influencing the masses to worship as they did in Jesus' time, adhering solely to his ideas, the church as an institution will remain strong to guide the way. However, as the theological clock moves backward, the extreme proliferation of diversity within Christendom will reverse into greater uniformity of belief and practice. Between regions, denominations, and divisions, we'll see increasing similarities. Human history is filled with such reversals. For instance, Christians were once persecuted, shunned, and killed by the Roman Empire, but later the empire itself became a Christian institution. Our nation has moved from African-American slavery to African-American leadership. The great reversion coming in our future will play out in the realm of the Christian religion, undoing history in search of the source and reducing diversity in the process. What's more, it will become common to read Jesus' words metaphorically, not as literal statements. So, what changed since Jesus' lifetime?

Looking back through history, we find that Judaism was the theological foundation for Christianity. Monotheism, the belief in a divinely revealed religion, and the authority of the Hebrew scriptures were all central to the religion by the time the Romans took control of Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E. The Jewish population was not united. They were divided into factions like the Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, and Zealots, with the majority being ordinary people.

Another text that illustrates the inherent greed and self-centeredness of people is "The Jungle" by Upton Sinclair. This novel reveals how, at their core, humans are driven to prioritize their own interests and comfort, often neglecting those less fortunate. The owners and directors of the massive factories in the story exemplify this; their sole focus is on expanding their businesses regardless of the consequences. Sinclair uses vivid imagery to depict the detrimental effects of this unchecked power, describing the factories as "a seething cauldron of jealousies and hatreds," with "great chimneys" spewing smoke and "massive" piles of animal waste. The workers are also subjected to harsh conditions, with employers prioritizing profits over their employees' well-being. With minimal legal protections and worker representation, the environment is akin to a system of slavery, with workers "dependent for its opportunities of life upon the whim of men every bit as brutal and unscrupulous as the old-time slave drivers."

Fitzgerald employs various techniques to evoke certain feelings or attitudes in his readers regarding crucial themes in "The Great Gatsby." Some of these approaches are more potent than others. F. Scott Fitzgerald utilizes a mix of adjective-noun pairings and symbolism in his novel to achieve this. He pairs seemingly mismatched adjectives and nouns to create a specific atmosphere around certain subjects. For instance, he often uses color to convey deeper meanings. In "The Great Gatsby," Fitzgerald assigns symbolic significance to colors like gold, green, white/gray, and red/pink. He builds up these meanings and then later uses them to evoke feelings around key objects.

White and gray are significant colors in Fitzgerald's novel. White symbolizes elegance and refinement, while gray represents aging and fading. He reinforces these meanings throughout the story. Daisy and Jordan wear white frequently, as do other characters in various scenes. For example, when Nick attends Gatsby’s party, he observes that people are dressed in white flannels, while Tom is seen in a white shirt when he meets Myrtle. Notably, only when Nick gets impressions of Gatsby’s party do people not wear white, suggesting a shift in importance. Common or unimportant subjects are also described in these colors: Nick travels “down the white chasms of lower New York,” and people at Gatsby’s party have “gray names.” Even mundane characters and settings are described in this way, such as Jordan and Daisy’s “white girlhood,” the “gray cars” and “gray land” in the valley of ashes, and the “gray” Italian child in the railroad.

Once Fitzgerald establishes the meanings of white/gray, he uses them to underscore unimportance or uniformity. This technique starts with Daisy. After a prolonged period without noticeable use of these colors, Daisy is described as wearing white in a white roadster. This description signals to readers that Daisy is less of a central character and more of a uniform addition to the story, someone Gatsby longs for. Fitzgerald uses similar descriptions of Daisy to reinforce this impression, such as her “gray haze of Daisy’s fur collar” and her white dress during the encounter between Tom and Gatsby.

San Diego County is a hot spot for agriculture due to its warm, sunny climate. The region is known for growing tomatoes, citrus fruits, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, tree fruits like peaches and lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. There's a thriving market for organic, community-supported agriculture, with many local groups having long waiting lists. Organic eggs and milk are also highly sought after in the San Diego area. Many organic farms offer tours and recreational activities like hiking and birdwatching, thereby allowing the landowner to enjoy the benefits of government programs while enhancing biodiversity and creating additional income streams. This type of operation not only fills a potentially profitable niche but also promotes a healthier environment by reducing chemical use, which in turn boosts both plant and wildlife diversity.

However, organic farming comes with its own set of challenges. It demands more intensive labor for pest control, weed management, and soil fertilization without chemicals. Furthermore, it can be less efficient and more costly than conventional farming, with smaller farms lacking the economies of scale. Additional wildlife-friendly practices, like planting cover crops or managing grazing rotation, can also increase labor costs. For these reasons, a landowner in this scenario might consider seeking financial assistance or expert advice to optimize both profits and habitat quality.

The land in question is a 160-acre parcel near the town of Potrero, in unincorporated San Diego County, California. It's a mix of chaparral, nonnative Mediterranean grassland, and oak woodland adjacent to the Cleveland National Forest. This area falls within the East County Southern Foothills ecoregion of the San Diego Multiple Species Conservation Plan. The plan currently identifies over a hundred plant and animal species, including several endangered ones like the Stephens' kangaroo rat, the mountain yellow-legged frog, several butterfly species, and the California gnatcatcher, as well as species that may soon be listed as declining.

Historically, the land was inhabited by Native Americans and later settled by cattle ranchers and cordwood sellers in the late 1800s. This parcel was part of an original homestead patent and was likely used for grazing and wood production over many decades. I selected this property from a real estate website and researched available government programs to see how a small farmer might reduce costs and maintain wildlife-friendly farming practices. As a model, I looked at an organic farm in the same area.

So another month has gone by, and once again, I find myself reflecting on how culture plays a substantial role in any negotiation. Culture, you see, is not a monolith, but rather a living thing that's as much about what it is not as what it is. It's not singular, uniform, or homogenous. Saying "all Russians are stubborn" or "all Japanese are accommodating" are oversimplifications, though understanding those generalizations can be beneficial. But it's far more practical for a negotiator to focus on how the culture's attitudes and values will impact the negotiations at hand. When encountering a foreign culture, it's natural to compare it to our own, which can present its own set of challenges.

The fool hath said in his heart, 'There is no God.'" The preceding quotation is found in Psalm 14 of the Christian Bible, and it serves as the opening point for St. Anselm's argument regarding the existence of God. A similar belief is held by another author we will discuss, St. Thomas Aquinas. Since both arguments argue for the existence of the same divine entity, our task is to determine whose argument is more compelling. For the sake of conciseness, we'll assume they're both correct in their belief in the biblical God. To explore their arguments fairly, we must consider a specific concept of God, as their defenses are tailored to that.

Starting with St. Anselm's basic argument, he suggests that understanding God begins with faith and self-reflection. He posits that because God's existence is inherent in our understanding, we cannot imagine Him not existing. While his concept can be somewhat obscure and complicated, the core idea is that God's proof lies within our own minds. We don't need external evidence; instead, we discover the truth about God through introspection. This is often referred to within Christianity as faith.

St. Thomas Aquinas, however, argues that God's existence can be proven through reason and empirical evidence, without requiring faith. This approach could be advantageous for evangelism, as it would allow for the persuasion of new converts based solely on logic. Aquinas presents five logical arguments supporting God's existence: change, causation, contingency, degrees of excellence, and harmony. Each argument essentially demonstrates that God's existence is logically necessary.

So, way back in the fifth or sixth century BCE, a man was born who would later come to be known as Buddha. After a life of renouncing the world, he attained enlightenment, and his teachings spread, eventually leading to the formation of Buddhism—the most traditional branch of which is called Theravada Buddhism. This religion is now around twenty-five hundred years old, and it's changed a lot since Buddha's time. For instance, in Sri Lanka, where Theravada Buddhism is practiced, the annual water-cutting ceremony is observed. Though Buddha never taught about such festivities, monks and laypeople alike participate, highlighting how the religion has evolved. These changes can be seen in everything from surface-level traditions to the very core of the religion's teachings. The Theravada Buddhist community has had to adapt its doctrinal principles over time due to both internal and external influences, some hostile and some benign.

There are some key terms we'll use often in this discussion: internal versus external, and hostile versus benign. Internal forces are those that come from within the Buddhist community, no matter the monastic status. External forces are anything from outside the community. A hostile force is anything that harms or intends to harm the Buddhist community, often due to a negative perception of Buddhism. A benign force, on the other hand, doesn't mean to harm or help the community—though it might end up doing so.

First, let's look at the basics of the religion—the core doctrines of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists seek refuge in the triple gem: the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma is essentially made up of the Tripitaka, the three baskets of Buddhist texts. The Sutta Pitaka contains all the Suttas, the Vinaya Pitaka sets out the disciplinary rules, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka delves into the metaphysical aspects of Buddhism, like Anatta (no self), Dukkha (inherent suffering), and Anicca (impermanence). Only by understanding these concepts can one escape Sansara, the cycle of death and rebirth. This escape also involves the elimination of lobha (desire), dosa (hatred), and moha (delusion), when one becomes enlightened.

In the Vinaya Pitaka, there are rules for laypeople and monks alike. Laypeople follow the Five Precepts (I shall not kill, I shall not lie, I shall not steal, I shall not misbehave sexually, and I shall not take intoxicating substances). Monks have many more rules to follow. The most fundamental teaching in Buddhism is the Four Noble Truths. First, life is suffering (Dukkha). Second, attachment causes suffering. Third, suffering can be overcome.

The United States and Mexico once shared a 57-year rivalry, from 1836 to 1893, with the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848 being the peak of their rivalry. This period saw many skirmishes before the First World War, with disputes often stemming from differences in religion, culture, and traditions, as well as competing material interests. Many nations with shared borders face similar situations, with David M. Pletcher noting that only in Mexico and Cuba can one find long-lasting, overarching American diplomatic problems. These nations are close geographically to the United States and have historically been rivals, while others in Latin America have maintained better relations. Religious differences, like those between the United States and Mexico, have caused rifts throughout history, similar to the ideological struggles during the Cold War between the United States and the Soviet Union. Diehl and Goerts list 17 disputes between Mexico and the United States during this period, with most being territorial issues related to border raids and frontier problems. Schmitt explains that the rivalry began to ease as Mexico grew more dependent on the United States, and it ended as American ambitions shifted from territorial expansion to economic intervention into Mexico in the late 19th century.

Fifteen years ago, I was suddenly and unexpectedly disabled by an illness I had never known existed. Prior to this, I was a nurse, having chosen this profession out of a strong desire for the stability and security I lacked as a child. The phrase, "You'll always find work; people will always get sick," echoed through my adolescence and beyond, guiding me towards nursing. Despite my dream of becoming a scientist or journalist, I found solace in the predictability of my chosen profession.

Yet, here I am: 46 years old, single, and unable to work, with no savings and living on Social Security Disability. After 15 years, I have nothing to call my own. Every day is a struggle, an assault on my security, safety, and self-esteem. Nothing is certain anymore, but one thing is clear: I could not have survived this long without the help of my family and a few good friends. When disaster strikes, you feel weak, no matter how strong you are.

My point is that life, both big and small, presents emergencies. There are no guarantees, and no matter how well you prepare, some things are too vast to overcome alone. While I agree that we should reduce our reliance on big government, I believe in the power of community. We should relearn to trust and help each other rather than each of us building our own fallout shelters.

Conservatives often praise "rugged individualism" as the nation's backbone, but our forefathers' resilience was built on compassion, mutual respect, and resource sharing. Pioneers crossing the Rockies didn't make it alone; they traveled in wagon trains, supporting each other.

So, yes, be prepared. I have a disaster kit, including first aid supplies, water purifying tablets, and flashlights. But while you're preparing, get to know your neighbors. Trust and community are just as important as personal preparedness.

So, why do organisms evolve as they do? Are there any restrictions or constraints that dictate the direction of evolutionary change? Back in 1917, D'Arcy Thompson had this to say: "Even now, the zoologist has scarcely begun to dream of defining in mathematical language even the simplest organic forms." Yet, we find ourselves still grappling with the same question today. Fortunately, mathematical modeling has made strides in understanding various aspects of mollusk skeletogenesis, both through ontogeny and phylogeny. Our research explores how these mathematical models, combined with experimental studies, can shed light on the mechanisms driving the direction and scale of evolutionary-change in Prunum. We've utilized X-radiographic images of Prunum species to quantify parameters that can be used to model both hypothetical and actual skeletal morphologies. These parameters were input into the software program CerioShell. We then modeled hypothetical shell morphologies to interpret possible morphological changes in Prunum, merging these results with experimental and descriptive studies to better grasp macroevolutionary events in this group.

A shell can be visualized as a structure that winds around through 360 degrees of space over time. These turns, or whorls, spiral around an imaginary central axis, the columella, which runs through the shell's central column. The rate at which these whorls enlarge varies, and the continuous line separating each whorl is called a suture. In most shells, the largest whorl is the last one, known as the body whorl. The spire consists of all whorls except the last, with the apex at the top and the base at the bottom. The animal exits the shell through an opening called the aperture.

Shells can be viewed from different angles: apical, basal, apertural, and abapertural. The usual orientation is the apertural view, with the aperture facing the viewer and the apex pointing up.

To count whorls, first view the shell from the apical side and determine where the first suture begins. Draw a line dividing the shell into two parts, and count from this line, estimating each whorl to a quarter of a full turn.

A shell can also be seen as a series of apertures that traverse time and space as the animal builds its shell. The path of the aperture can be tracked via the coordinates of each whorl's aperture and its horizontal and vertical radii.

This trajectory can be graphically and mathematically represented. Once a formulation is created, parameters can be varied to modify the mollusk's skeletogenesis.

Well, I've been watching the stats on neonatal and infant mortality in Indonesia for a while now, and it seems like there's barely been any progress over the last decade. While the country's on a good track to meet certain Millennium Development Goals, like water and sanitation, we're falling short on child and maternal health. There are a bunch of reasons why, and it seems like we need to focus more on strengthening the overall health system instead of just tweaking individual programs.

We've seen a decent improvement in the number of births attended by skilled health workers, with 72% meeting the target. But a lot of these are just traditional workers like midwives, who can't handle complicated pregnancies, leading to a lot of maternal deaths from things like hemorrhage. So, these improvements are a bit misleading, and we still have a lot of work to do. Plus, the percentage of children under five getting treatment for diarrhea has gone down, and data on postnatal care is all over the place.

Cesarean-section rates are still lower than they should be, around 4%, and there's a big gap between urban and rural rates. This shows that healthcare access is mainly focused on cities. And there's a huge gap in service use between the poorest and richest people, which is likely due to high out-of-pocket costs. So, we need to ask ourselves how to best tackle these issues. Should we focus on specific programs or strengthen the health system as a whole? There are pros and cons to both approaches.

Program-specific solutions are a great way to tackle specific problems, but they can also lead to duplication and lack of coordination. Plus, they might take funding away from other important areas. So, we need to find a balance to improve neonatal and maternal care indicators.

Victorian literature is renowned for its meticulous attention to detail and its focus on the aristocracy of the time. However, two notable exceptions are Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights, which diverge from this norm by incorporating elements of mystery and surprise, atypical for the period. These elements enhance the characters within each work, deepening insights into their motivations and emotions. For instance, the protagonist in Oliver Twist experiences vivid dreamlike sequences that reveal his inner self, the struggles he faces, and his awareness of the true nature of his surroundings. When revisiting the event of his shooting in chapter 28, Oliver relives the experience in a dreamlike state, highlighting his lack of control over the events and the dire straits his health has been in. His hallucinations of Sikes and Crackit emphasize his despair, and the shooting itself numbs all his senses, leaving him feeling overwhelmed and defeated. This event raises questions about whose will is manipulating his misfortune, as it's clear it's not his own. The shooting also underscores Oliver's lack of control over life events, reinforcing the notion that he doesn't even attempt to assert control when his life is in danger. This suggests a growing sense of defeat, as if his mentor, Fagin, has begun to break him, compelling him to accept this despair and severely impacting his ability to react.

A couple of years ago, I was tutoring in an after-school program for elementary-age students. My forte was English and reading, but I was recruited by a teacher to help a boy named Adrian, who was struggling with reading. He was in third or fourth grade, and something seemed off. He could pronounce certain letters perfectly, but others, not at all. I realized he could read but didn't know the English alphabet well. His mother spoke only Spanish, and with my limited Spanish, we communicated, but I understood then: Adrian needed tutoring in English reading, specifically on the alphabet and pronunciation. I'm not sure if this helped him much, but I hope he's doing better now.

I share this story to highlight the language barrier in schools, especially in California. It's not always as apparent as we think. Even a child speaking perfect English may struggle with reading. Everyone agrees this problem exists, so what's the solution? For Adrian, it was simple: English reading tutoring. But for children barely speaking English, it's more complex. There's no one-size-fits-all answer. The dual language system, mainstream immersion, private tutors, ESL classes—none alone will solve this. The key is combining all these approaches.

Firstly, the dual language system is excellent. It benefits children whose first language is Spanish but also those learning English. Research shows children in bilingual programs outperform their peers. People fear it's a resource waste, but that's false. If implemented widely, all children would benefit. But how do we do it? Requiring all teachers to be bilingual? No, that's unreasonable. Instead, we could employ bilingual aids or tutors.

From the time we are children, many of us are told that there is something out there that is larger than ourselves, something we can't fully understand. Some of us learn about it in Sunday school, others in temples, or within ourselves. We often accept the religions passed down by our parents, but some of us reject them completely, believing that there's nothing beyond our own personal egocentric universe. We may embrace one belief system only to later change our minds and adopt another. Whatever path we choose, we journey to define a part of ourselves through our unique spiritual perspectives. We search for a guiding light to lead us out of the shadows and into the sun.

“A cardinal,” my father said when I asked him what his favorite type of bird was. We were sitting on the front porch of our house, listening to the rain beat down on the tin roof as we smoked our cigarettes together. The gutters were overflowing, drenching the plants along the edge of the porch. He stared out into the rain, a look that seemed both searching and reminiscing. He had grown gaunt over the past few months, his clothes hanging loosely on his frame, and his hair thinner and sparser than I remembered. He continued to gaze out into the rain, avoiding my eyes. I felt alone, scared, and unable to talk to my father about how much I would miss him because admitting it would only make it more real for both of us. I hugged him, sat back down, moved my chair closer to his, and joined him in looking out into the June twilight rain.

My father passed away in December of that year, just five days after my twenty-second birthday. The chemo and radiation had prolonged his suffering but extended his life a few more months beyond what the doctors had predicted. I couldn't understand the value of this when it just meant more suffering. I thought to myself, "What kind of God would do this?" Alone in the night, I refused to pray. If God existed, I believed he had stopped listening to me long ago.

I didn't want to watch him leave this life to enter another. So I didn't. I couldn't watch the life that created me as it ended. I wanted to remember my father by how he lived, not how he died. Besides, I knew my father better than anyone, better than his own family, and I was sure he wouldn't want his only child to be a spectator at his death. I curled up in a ball in my bed for three days, waiting for the news.

No one even called me.

Well, I have this affliction called shyness. Every time I talk to strangers, especially to one of the opposite sex, I turn into jello. I can't think, I start to tremble and I basically just freeze up. It doesn't happen all the time nowadays but it happened today at the YEN meeting. I had to tell Genevieve that I hadn't received the invitation to the club mailing list yet. I thought I could do it without any trouble but I was obviously wrong. In my humble opinion, unless you are mentally incapacitated, you and only yourself are responsible for the life that you lead. There is no two ways about it. Well, I was just in one of my rhetoric moods just now. I was thinking of how sad it was that good friends can grow apart as you grow up. You gain new perspectives as you grow and those might not be the same as your friends. Like you're in different realities. Sometimes you grow apart because of differing views and sometimes it's because of circumstances. Some of which are not under your control but most of which are. Things like gaining a new ideological belief, new social groups, or just something as simple as getting a new job. Any of which can cause you to not make contact as often as you would like. I used to believe that it was their fault for not keeping in touch. But then I realized that I was as much at fault as anyone else in my life. People walk in and walk out of your life. You can try to keep them from walking out but ultimately, it's their choice. Guess that's why you have to choose your friends carefully. But then again, if you are too guarded in your choices, you might be artificially restricting yourself. Ah the choices we all make. I've had many good people in my life. It's sad to reminisce on the good times past as you know the chances of regaining those times are slim to none. So there's no use dwelling on them. But you don't want to discount their value in helping to shape you into the person that you are today. And yet, you don't want to let them hold you back from becoming the person that you're going to be tomorrow. Sigh. This doesn't happen much when you're a teenager but it starts when you reach adulthood. You wish to be as carefree as you were then. Letting your parents worry for you. Reality was just for other people. You lived in a cocoon, in your own world. Ah the good old days.

Alright, so supply chain management is all about moving goods from when you first get an order from a customer right down to when the product eventually reaches them. This term was coined in 1982 by a consultant named Keith Oliver. He described it as the process of planning, implementing, and controlling all the activities involved in the supply chain to ensure customer satisfaction in a quick and efficient manner. There are six main components to a supply chain: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. Business managers use these six elements to deliver the best possible service to their customers.

Starting with production, which is the first and most crucial step in the supply chain. Production lays the groundwork for the entire process. Managers need to know what their customers want, so they look at the market to determine customer demand. Once they understand what customers need, they can decide what products to produce and how many of each to make. After that, they choose where to produce these products, considering factors like volume and quality, and always keeping customer satisfaction in mind.

Once the production location is set, managers focus on scheduling workloads and maintaining equipment. Production is a critical step, and every detail must be planned meticulously. For instance, I used to work at Wal-Mart and Target, and both companies have designed processes for every aspect of their operations. Having these outlined processes ensures smooth operation without confusion or misunderstandings about expectations and directions.

The next key element is supply. Supply involves making strategic decisions about the core capabilities of a facility and forming outsourcing partnerships. A company might have multiple divisions for producing a single product, each with its own equipment, workers, and specialties. The manager must choose the best division for each product process. They may also decide to outsource work to other companies to increase velocity. Velocity means providing quality and flexibility while keeping costs low or maintaining low cost levels.

Every month that goes by, and I'm left here, barely moving. Not much happens, except for the tales I'm about to spin. In Burma, a sign reads that Hitler is alive. Ellen Page, the star of Juno, stands alone on a street corner, a cardboard message held high above her head, handwritten in Sharpie. Burma, or Myanmar, is a country ruled by a tyrannical military regime since 1962. In 2007, monks led a wave of public protests, known as "The Saffron Revolution." Initially, the government allowed these peaceful gatherings, but soon violence erupted. Monasteries were invaded, and foreign journalists were imprisoned, with one photojournalist, Kenji Nagai, killed on Sept 27, 2007, just for being at a protest. The official death toll is 13, but Colonel Hla Win, a defector, claims thousands were killed.

This isn't new. Throughout history, governments have crushed dissent to maintain power. Roman emperors declared themselves divine rulers, Japanese emperors are believed to be gods, and our current president, George W. Bush, has a weekly meeting with Ted Haggard, leader of Stupid People Worldwide, a branch of the Republican Party.

Tiananmen Square in 1989, where intellectuals and students protested authoritarian rule, and the Rwandan genocide of the 1990s, where Hutu militia slaughtered Tutsis and political moderates, are examples of this. Hitler's Third Reich, where Jews were systematically murdered, is another extreme case.

This is the reality of our world, where power is often wielded without regard for human rights.

Well, Duke Ellington's name is synonymous with jazz for a reason. He had this uncanny ability to keep his orchestra together for decades, which allowed him to fully explore his creative prowess. While his keyboard skills were often understated in his compositions, as a composer, he was a master at crafting intricate pieces that highlighted each band member's unique abilities. Ellington created a framework where soloists could freely improvise, and he also wrote tightly orchestrated phrases that emphasized the specific styles of his musicians to bring out musical ideas. This balance of structure and freedom allowed him to create some of the most innovative and brilliant pieces in jazz history. The Grove Music dictionary even mentions the Creole Love Call, an early example of Ellington's use of voice as a jazz instrument. This slow, twelve-bar blues piece showcases his ability to complement his soloists and add layers of sound. The piece features a call and response between voice and reeds, with different sections echoing and elaborating on the basic melody. The use of voice and tone color is a stylistic trait that runs throughout Ellington's work. In Hot and Bothered, recorded a year later, Ellington combines his skill at tight orchestration with his ear for tone color, creating a rich and complementary sound between a muted trumpet and scat singing. Don't Mean a Thing (If It Ain't Got That Swing) showcases his use of muted trombone to great effect, further illustrating his mastery of individual sounds and their combination.
