So, I've got some news for you. This study was all about proving that sticking to a Mediterranean diet (Med diet), especially one that's high in "alternative Mediterranean" diet score, can lower your risk of chronic heart disease and stroke, as well as stroke-related death. Now, the alternative Mediterranean diet is basically a tweaked version of the traditional Med diet, focusing on eating more plant foods like fruits, nuts, whole grains, and legumes, and less animal products and saturated fats. It also allows for moderate alcohol consumption.

Now, previous research has shown that following the Med diet can reduce the risk of dying from cardiovascular issues, and it's more effective than a low-fat diet for weight loss and improving cholesterol levels in overweight people. However, this study is one of the first to look specifically at stroke and stroke-related deaths.

This study tracked 74,886 women aged 38 to 63 who were part of the Nurses' Health Study, a group of 121,700 nurses in 11 US states. Every six years from 1984 to 2004, these women filled out food frequency questionnaires, which were used to calculate their 'alternative Mediterranean' diet scores. These scores were based on their nutrient intake over the past year. Around 95% of these nurses stayed in the study for the entire 20 years. Their food intake data was validated, and reports of heart disease, stroke, and death were verified through medical or hospital records, autopsies, or death certificates. Cases where records weren't available were considered "probable" and included in the study.

To account for any individual variations and give a better representation of long-term eating habits, the study used average scores from two years of repeated questionnaires. Adjustments were made for factors that could skew the results, like age, smoking, body mass index, menopausal status, hormone use, multivitamin intake, alcohol consumption, physical activity, and aspirin use.

The study used a statistical method called Cox proportional-hazard modeling to see how these diet scores were linked to heart disease and stroke risks. The results? Women who stuck closely to the Mediterranean diet had a lower risk of heart disease and stroke. Over the 20 years, there were 2,391 new cases of heart disease, 1,763 cases of stroke, and 1,077 cardiovascular deaths. Those who scored highest on the alternative Mediterranean diet had a 29% lower risk of heart disease and stroke compared to those who scored the lowest.

Alright, so let's rewind to 2007, and oh boy, did the United States face a real financial powder keg. Unemployment skyrocketed, the housing market tanked, and some of America's most pivotal corporations were left for dead. This economic downturn is still with us today, so let's delve into how this all went down and how we can prevent it from happening again. Well, the financial crisis was basically a result of arrogant and careless political decision-making that pushed banks and firms into issuing sub-prime loans to an underdeveloped financial infrastructure. Meanwhile, Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac were pushed to underwrite and repack these mortgages into CDOs and CDS'. When borrowers defaulted on these loans, banks were left with insufficient capital reserves and passed the chaos onto the repacked mortgages they sold, and on to the rest of the economy.

The seeds of this disaster were planted in 1999 during the Clinton administration. The president was aiming for a second term and sought to boost his popularity by easing lending restrictions, which set the stage for the sub-prime crisis seven years later. Steven Holmes of the New York Times warned in 1999, “Fannie Mae has been pressured by the Clinton Administration to expand mortgage loans among low and moderate income people, and felt pressure from stockholders to maintain its impressive growth in profits.” Holmes accurately predicted the consequences: “But the government-subsidized corporation may face trouble in an economic downturn, prompting a government rescue like that of the savings and loan industry in the 1980s.” As we see in the introduction, and as Holmes foresaw, ill-fated lending led to the economy's meltdown.

Several factors combined to bring the economy to its knees, one being the new and complex mortgage structures. Adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and CDOs were widely used in the lead-up to the crisis, further entangling the economy in the housing market. This led to households and financial markets over-leveraging in the housing market, making them extremely sensitive to price changes.

Indeed, the housing bubble burst, leaving financial institutions that had bought these mortgage-backed securities in the red. The top five U.S. investment banks collectively reported $4.1 trillion in mortgage debts in 2007, which accounted for about 30% of the USA’s GDP. Bear Sterns and Merrill Lynch were quickly sold off cheap, Lehman Brothers was dismantled, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley were forced to become commercial banks under intense regulation. Fannie and Freddie racked up $5 trillion in mortgage debt and were placed under government control in September 2008.

Ah, exposition. That place in your story where you stretch your little writer's wings and take flight, captivating one and all with your magnetic, nay magical prose. Or the part where your readers fall asleep and/or hit the "Back" button while cursing your name. Dr. Merlin has been known to shout at her monitor when she finds herself in the middle of Too Much Information, and not even in the fun way.

Exposition is not your friend.

My gentle readers already know the basic writing tip, "Show, don't tell," but Dr. Merlin still stumbles into long passages of text where nothing happens, or worse, too much. Exposition is the little devil sitting on your shoulder that says to get the history out of the way to get to the good parts (not to be confused with the devil sitting on the other shoulder urging the author to tell her audience every single detail of the childhoods of each character).

Exposition means telling the audience what happened, typically in simple prose. In film, the exposition happens when one character tells another a core-dump of information ala "The Rime of the Ancient Mariner." In fiction, the author's doing the telling.

An example is in order. As you are reading a story, you are told that the heroine met her beloved at such a place and time, that they were married in a gala fashion, and that her husband was murdered in front of her eyes. You would not expect this entire sequence to take two pages, during which time both he and she only get two lines of dialogue each. You would expect the author to spend some time on the husband's character, evidencing by his speech and manner how deeply he loves his wife, and you would equally expect the heroine to show through big and small ways how much his presence in her life changed and enriched her (especially if the story were to tell you flat out later that this was the case). A proper introduction to the husband's character would allow you to become emotionally involved with his fate and would give you insight into the heroine's character: what she saw in him, how deep their bond was, clues about her thoughts and beliefs and dreams as reflected through the prism of his eyes, and so on. You would mourn his death with her, and so grow more connected to the heroine herself.

In short, you would expect meat on the simple bone of the storyline: "They met, they married, he died."

As a writer, you need to provide that meat. (*looks at metaphor, sighs, plunges onward*) Sometimes it is tempting to rush past certain things. Perhaps you're introducing a new character and you know he used to be in the Air Force, and he's the night manager of a gas station now, and he was married twice, no kids, likes to go fishing on the weekends, secretly dreams of owning the gas station someday and had Eggs Benedict for breakfast.

Watched two news broadcasts from Columbus, Ohio. The first, which was a live segment, was NBC 4 this morning (August 13, 2011). The headline was about a man named Shad Hostettler from Ashley, Ohio, who had stabbed his wife. Her name was not mentioned, but his mug shot showed a man who looked menacing. They gave it a mere two minutes, which I thought was sufficient given it was still unfolding. The only details they provided were that he had stabbed her multiple times and was arrested. I thought they gave it appropriate coverage.
The second story was about an early morning shooting of Travis Buyers, an 18-year-old, in the Sharon Woods area. He was critically injured, and no arrests had been made. The SWAT team was investigating. This story seemed short, and I believe that might have been due to a racial bias. I've noticed over the years that minority victims of crime, especially black ones, often get less attention. For instance, if a white child or adult is kidnapped or a victim of a crime, the media goes into overdrive, but minority victims often get bypassed.
The next story was about a bullet hole found in a Med-Flight helicopter. Details were given about the incident's location, and it was determined to be a .22 caliber bullet from a rifle. Crime-Stoppers offered a $5,000 reward for tips leading to the shooter's arrest.
The next story was about rain and thunderstorms predicted for Saturday afternoon. They predicted mid to low eighties for the weekend, but the news was short and served as a teaser to keep viewers engaged.
Another story was about a robbery at a Clime Road UDF in Columbus. A dark-skinned black man, described as about six-foot tall and 150 pounds, was the suspect. He was wearing a hoodie sweatshirt. They devoted an unusual amount of time emphasizing his race and how dark he was.
The final story was about Rene Rodriguez, a convicted Texas drug kingpin, who had been sentenced to distribute marijuana in large amounts to Ohio from Texas. Instead of saying he was sentenced to 25 years, they said "300" months. I'm not sure why they used this phrasing; perhaps to make the sentence sound more harsh. They also mentioned he was Hispanic, which I didn't think was relevant to the story.

There exists a special bond between brothers; one that's unbreakable and irrevocable, carrying with it a mix of emotions like love, pride, jealousy, and cruelty. These siblings understand each other more than anyone else could, and seeing their reflection in each other's eyes reveals their true selves. This bond shows its true colors in dire situations, be it for good or ill, and the consequences of these emotions are substantial. By facing these feelings head-on, one can begin to grasp the reality of the bond and the impact it has on their character. “The Scarlet Ibis” explores this theme through the vivid descriptions of a captivating landscape and the interactions between the two brothers involved. The main character, Doodle, and the narrator's perspective present the complex emotions and viewpoints that shape their actions and drive their journey. One emotion stands out above the rest: pride. From their initial outings to their final, tragic adventure, the protagonist feels resentment towards his younger brother Doodle. He initially dreams of teaching him various skills, like holding his breath, running, and climbing, but Doodle's weak heart makes these dreams impossible. The protagonist's heart softens, though, when Doodle smiles at him, revealing a deep-seated love within him.

The human brain is a complex, imaginative information-processing machine. As technology evolved from simple to advanced, the analogies used to describe the brain also evolved. Initially, it was likened to a wax tablet, then to a sheet of papyrus, then to a tome of written words, and most recently, to a computer. As you delve into the intricacies of the brain, remember that these analogies are limited in their usefulness and can lead to misleading conclusions.

Information processing commences with inputs from the sensory organs, converting physical stimuli like touch, heat, sound waves, or light particles into electrochemical signals. These sensory inputs are repeatedly transformed by the brain's algorithms in both bottom-up and top-down processing. For instance, when contemplating an image of a black box on a white background, bottom-up processing merges basic information such as color, direction, and border locations to determine the presence of a box. Top-down processing speeds up this recognition by leveraging decisions from earlier stages of bottom-up processing, potentially helping you recognize the object as a black box rather than a box-shaped void in the white background.

Once information is sufficiently processed, an attention filter evaluates its importance and decides which cognitive processes it should be made accessible to. For example, while your brain processes every blade of grass when you gaze at your shoes, a functional attention filter ensures that you don't notice each one individually. Conversely, you might pick out your name even when spoken amidst noise. There are numerous stages of information processing, with attention modulating the results at each stage.

For the brain to process information, storage is essential. Multiple types of memory exist, including sensory, working, and long-term. First, information is encoded. Each type of sensory stimulus has its own encoding method. For instance, verbal input can be encoded structurally, phonemically, or semantically. Once information is stored, it must be retained. Some animal studies suggest that working memory, active for about 20 seconds, is maintained through an electrical signal looping through specific neurons for a brief period. Long-term memory is hypothesized to be retained in the structure of certain proteins.

Various models propose how knowledge is organized in the brain, drawn from human memory retrieval, computer science, and neurophysiology. The semantic network model posits that concepts are represented by nodes, and nodes are connected based on their relevance. For example, in a semantic network, “chair” might be linked to “table,” which could be linked to “wooden,” and so forth.

Aldous Huxley takes aim at the impending threats of both technology and the capitalist system that perpetuates them through the creation of a dystopian society in Brave New World. The citizens are conditioned from birth to prioritize collective happiness over individuality, ensnared in a system that treats them as pawns in a grand game controlled by the World Controller. By examining his work through a Marxist lens, one can uncover Huxley's reservations about the evolution of these systems. Terms like homogeny and reification underscore his critique of the emergent economic order of his time.

Capitalism is skewered through the Marxist concept of false consciousness, where the common people are blinded from understanding their economic relations to other classes. They are focused solely on personal gain, a result of ideological control, evident in the conditioning of the people in Brave New World. The lower classes, such as Deltas and Gammas, are manipulated into a constant state of consumption and indulgence, oblivious to the manipulation. This is an example of hegemony, where the upper classes, though aware, do little to challenge the system. Interactions between social classes are a stark indicator of capitalist oppression.

The novel portrays a world where genuine human connections are absent. Characters are indistinguishable, even among the main ones, lacking depth. Perhaps Huxley is hinting that technology and capitalism together strip people of free will and individuality. Emotions like love and deep affection are nonexistent, with interactions kept superficial. For instance, men’s comments about women are often solely about their physical attributes, and women casually discuss their encounters. This societal complacency with their status within the hierarchy reflects Marxist thought on the proletariat, who are falsely assured of their superiority so long as they continue to consume and conform.

So here I am, a student at University Park for a couple of years now, or roughly four and a half semesters to be specific. Navigating around campus can be quite a hassle, just as it is for many others. My first year, I was housed in an East Halls dorm room, pretty much the easternmost point of campus, not counting the stadium and Bryce Jordan Center. Getting to classes like those in Willard building, smack dab in the middle of campus, could take up to a quarter of an hour on foot, especially if the weather wasn't cooperating, which is quite often in State College. I chatted with an older alum who told me that not too long ago, the East Halls dorms were separated from the rest of the school by vast swathes of unused land. Now, that empty space is filled with sports fields, new buildings like the Creamery and health services, and apartments. As the campus expands, getting from one place to another becomes increasingly challenging. So, what's the best solution to this mobility issue? On a college campus, it's the bicycle. But a bike alone won't fix the problem. Students need to use them, and the campus must be designed with bicyclists in mind.

I was talking to a friend who recently started cycling again after a few years' break. He admitted he wondered why he ever stopped. “Bikes are fantastic,” he said, “they’re the only way to get around.” Cycling is not only good for your health but also the most efficient way to travel. A simple bowl of oatmeal and some physical activity can take you 30 miles or more. Like many undergraduates, I now live off campus, just as far from campus center as some dorms. The best decision I've made this year was to buy a bike. My daily class at Thomas building is a twenty-five-minute walk from my home. A bike can cut that time down to five minutes if I pedal fast enough. The only drawback is, Pollock Road, the most direct route to Thomas from my house, isn't always the easiest road to ride. Walking is an option too, but I'm just too busy for it. If I didn't have my bike, walking would be my only reliable way to get to class. Walking to Thomas every day would add an extra 30-40 minutes to my day, totaling more than two and a half hours every week. Add that to all the other time I'd need to walk for classes, appointments, and so on, and it's more time than I can spare.
